>
  <p>The most impressive AI demos show autonomy. The system receives a task, chooses tools, moves through steps, and produces an answer.</p>
  <p>That is useful for imagination. It is not enough for production.</p>

  <blockquote>The flashy demo is autonomy. The durable product is controlled autonomy.</blockquote>

  <h2>Autonomy needs boundaries</h2>
  <p>Inside a regulated enterprise, the important question is not whether an agent can act. The question is what it is allowed to do, with which evidence, under which policy, for which customer, and with what record of the decision.</p>
  <p>Autonomy without boundaries creates risk. Boundaries without workflow design create shelfware.</p>

  <h2>The product is the operating model</h2>
  <p>Controlled autonomy needs routing, retrieval, validation, logging, escalation, permission boundaries, and audit trails. These are not administrative details. They are what make the system usable.</p>
  <p>If an AI system can draft a communication but cannot explain the source, log the action, route the exception, or preserve the control record, it is not ready for regulated work.</p>

  <h2>Where AI must land</h2>
  <p>The durable value will not come from AI sitting beside the work. It will come from AI landing inside the systems where work actually moves: CRM, case management, advisor platforms, analytics, communications, service operations, and enterprise workflow.</p>
  <p>That is why enterprise AI is bigger than model access. It is a work-design problem.</p>

  <h2>The leadership test</h2>
  <p>Leaders should ask where the human returns, which decision rights change, what evidence the system uses, what the customer experiences, and how the enterprise will know whether the new workflow improved the outcome.</p>
  <p>Controlled autonomy is not a brake on innovation. It is the condition that makes innovation usable at institutional scale.</p>
</ArticleLayout>
